data.reasoningText:
Now I have a good understanding of the project. Let me plan the component decomposition and implement it.

## Component Plan: Settings Dashboard

### Component Tree
```
SettingsPage                    (page — route /settings, owns data + active section)
├── SettingsSidebar             (vertical tab nav)
├── ProfileSection              (profile editing)
├── NotificationsSection        (notification prefs)
├── SecuritySection             (security settings)
│   ├── ChangePasswordPanel     (expandable password form)
│   └── RevokeSessionDialog     (confirmation modal)
└── AppearanceSection           (appearance + live preview)


```

The data flows from SettingsPage down to each section as parameters, with sections triggering callbacks back up when the user saves changes. SettingsPage handles the service calls and toast notifications. I'll start by building the service contracts and models, then work through the leaf components before composing them into the larger sections.

I'm creating the models and service interface file first, then building out all the Razor components in dependency order — starting with the sidebar and individual panels, moving up through the composite sections, and finally the orchestrator page with styling and DI registration.

```

csharp
// Models/SettingsModels.cs
public record ChangePasswordRequest(string CurrentPassword, string NewPassword, string ConfirmPassword);
public record ChangePasswordResponse(bool Success, string Message);
public record SessionInfo(string SessionId, string DeviceName, DateTime CreatedAt, DateTime LastActivityAt, bool IsCurrent);
public record RevokeSessionRequest(string SessionId);
public interface ISettingsService
{
    Task<ChangePasswordResponse> ChangePasswordAsync(ChangePasswordRequest request);
    Task<List<SessionInfo>> GetSessionsAsync();
    Task RevokeSessionAsync(RevokeSessionRequest request);
}
```

Now I'm building the sidebar component that displays the navigation menu for different settings sections. Then I'll create the change password panel with form validation and error handling. After that, the revoke session dialog for managing active sessions. The profile, notifications, security, and appearance sections will each handle their respective settings areas. Finally, the main settings page will orchestrate all these components together with proper layout and styling using Bootstrap classes.

